Perfect! I found the issue. The `toPeriod()` method in `AbstractDuration` calls `new Period(getMillis())`, which in turn calls the BasePeriod constructor that takes a long as a parameter. Looking back at the BasePeriod constructor:

```java
protected BasePeriod(long duration, PeriodType type, Chronology chrono) {
    super();
    type = checkPeriodType(type);
    chrono = DateTimeUtils.getChronology(chrono);
    iType = type;
    iValues = chrono.get(this, duration);
}
```

And the constructor that just takes a `long duration`:

```java
protected BasePeriod(long duration) {
    this(duration, null, null);
    // bug [3264409]
}
```

This calls the previous constructor with null type and null chronology, which means `DateTimeUtils.getChronology(null)` will return the default chronology. But when the test is running, the default timezone has been set to a fixed offset timezone (`DateTimeZone.forOffsetHours(2)`), so the computation is affected by timezone calculations unnecessarily.

Looking at the test again, it expects a specific calculation where a duration of `(450 * 24) + 5` hours should appear in the hours field, but the timezone handling might be interfering.

Let me run the failing test again to see the exact error:

